#Text= I wo n't have them books here in the way ! " she cried petulantly ; and seizing them one by one she began throwing them upon the floor .

column1: #Text=" Leave my books alone ! " he said .
#Text=" You might have thrown them aside if you had liked , but as to soiling them like that , it is disgusting ! "
#Text=In the operation of making lard Arabella 's hands had become smeared with the hot grease , and her fingers consequently left very perceptible imprints on the book-covers .
#Text=She continued deliberately to toss the books severally upon the floor , till Jude , incensed beyond bearing , caught her by the arms to make her leave off .
#Text=Somehow , in going so , he loosened the fastening of her hair , and it rolled about her ears .
#Text=" Let me go ! " she said .
#Text=" Promise to leave the books alone . "
#Text=She hesitated .
#Text=" Let me go ! " she repeated .
#Text=" Promise ! "
#Text=After a pause :
#Text=" I do . "
#Text=Jude relinquished his hold , and she crossed the room to the door , out of which she went with a set face , and into the highway .
#Text=Here she began to saunter up and down , perversely pulling her hair into a worse disorder than he had caused , and unfastening several buttons of her gown .
#Text=It was a fine Sunday morning , dry , clear and frosty , and the bells of Alfredston Church could be heard on the breeze from the north .

#Text=People were going along the road , dressed in their holiday clothes ; they were mainly lovers -- such pairs as Jude and Arabella had been when they sported along the same track some months earlier .

#Text=These pedestrians turned to stare at the extraordinary spectacle she now presented , bonnetless , her dishevelled hair blowing in the wind , her bodice apart , her sleeves rolled above her elbows for her work , and her hands reeking with melted fat .
#Text=One of the passers said in mock terror : " Good Lord deliver us ! "
#Text=" See how he 's served me ! " she cried .
#Text=" Making me work Sunday mornings when I ought to be going to my church , and tearing my hair off my head , and my gown off my back ! "
#Text=Jude was exasperated , and went out to drag her in by main force .
#Text=Then he suddenly lost his heat .
#Text=Illuminated with the sense that all was over between them , and that it mattered not what she did , or he , her husband stood still , regarding her .

#Text=Their lives were ruined , he thought ; ruined by the fundamental error of their matrimonial union : that of having based a permanent contract on a temporary feeling which had no necessary connection with affinities that alone render a lifelong comradeship tolerable .
#Text=" Going to ill-use me on principle , as your father ill-used your mother , and your father 's sister ill-used her husband ? " she asked .
#Text=" All you be a queer lot as husbands and wives ! "
#Text=Jude fixed an arrested , surprised look on her .
#Text=But she said no more , and continued her saunter till she was tired .
#Text=He left the spot , and , after wandering vaguely a little while , walked in the direction of Marygreen .
#Text=Here he called upon his great-aunt , whose infirmities daily increased .
#Text=" Aunt -- did my father ill-use my mother , and my aunt her husband ? " said Jude abruptly , sitting down by the fire .
#Text=She raised her ancient eyes under the rim of the by-gone bonnet that she always wore .
#Text=" Who 's been telling you that ? " she said .
#Text=" I have heard it spoken of , and want to know all . "
#Text=" You med so well , I s'pose ; though your wife -- I reckon ' twas she -- must have been a fool to open up that !
